==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ja}} {{term|アニメ|lang=ja}} ''anime'', an abbreviation of {{term|アニメーション|lang=ja}} ''animēshon'', from English {{term|animation|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|En-us-anime.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|2=-|pl=anime|pl2=animes}}

# {{uncountable}} An artistic style heavily used in, and associated with, [[Japan]]ese [[animation]], and that has also been adopted by a comparatively low number of animated works from other [[country|countries]].
#* ''I can draw an '''anime''' version of you, if you want.''
# {{countable}} An animated work originated in [[Japan]], regardless of the artistic style.
#* '''2005''', Peter J. Katzenstein, ''A World of Regions'', page 165,
#*: After three months of successful sales in [[manga]] form, it was made into an '''anime''' for television.
#* '''2005''', [[w:Joan D. Vinge|Joan D. Vinge]], in ''The Year's Best Fantasy and Horror: Eighteenth Annual Collection'', page cix,
#*: Usually the manga comes first, though it may be an offshoot of a novel, and an '''anime''' may be inspired by a video game.
#* '''2006''', Thomas LaMarre, in ''Japan After Japan'' (Tomiko Yoda & Harry D. Harootunian, eds.), page 363,
#*: These '''anime''' prepared the way for ''Otaku no video'', a two-part Original Video Animation (OVA).
# {{rare|countable|chiefly|proscribed|_|by|_|fandom}} An animated work that uses the anime style, regardless of the country of origin.

